Case Study Scenario

In order to effectively fight wildfires, it is necessary for strike team commanders to have a strong understanding of topography. Fire burns upslope more quickly, which can pose challenges to fire fighting as well as firefighter safety.

READ: https://cnr.ncsu.edu/news/2021/12/explainer-how-wildfires-start-and-spread/

When there are fires like the Ferguson Fire in Mariposa in 2017, fire fighting teams from across the state come to help. This is called Mutual Aid - it brings together crews from cities, rural areas, state agencies, federal agencies, and other groups. Often times, crews will not be familiar with an area prior to arrival.

As a member of the Yosemite All Hazards Region Geospatial Coordination group, you’ve been tasked by the strike team commander to create a few basic raster map products to share with the crews for them to gain a better understanding of the local topography. This will enable more effective planning and attack.

You will also consider the ethical implications of producing data for emergency response.

Instructions

Part 1: Data Management

A Note on Data Management
WARNING: Raster datasets are often large! Depending on how they were they were encoded, they may also compress well. You need to extract all .zip files in order for your files to be read by ArcGIS Pro, or Excel (or most any other program).

Be mindful of your disk space, because some of these rasters expand to hundreds of megabytes when unzipped. You will need at least 1GB of free space for this lab. Have a plan for managing your data in your labs.

Part 2: Spatial operations with Raster data

For this lab, we will use a dataset from The National Map and the 3D Elevation Program (3DEP), a nation-wide DEM assembled by the United States Geological Survey. The 3DEP serves as the elevation layer for the national map (it formerly was the National Elevation Dataset [NED). For more information on the National Map and the 3DEP, refer to the project web pages [1, 2]. Again, the data you will use today was sourced from the NED [3,4].

• Add NED2013_mcd_mrp_albers.tif to a new Lab 5-1 Project in ArcGIS Pro. The file is located in the NED2013_mcd_mrp folder. If the software asks you to “Build Pyramids” or similar, select Yes/Ok. This should only take a minute or two. You can add the .tif in by drag and dropping it from your data folder into the Map window, or you can permanently add it to your geodatabase through the Raster to Geodatabase tool.

2.1 Slope
The Slope tool [5] in ArcGIS Pro computes the slope of the terrain at a given pixel, from the surrounding pixels. The slope value represents an angle, between zero (no slope) and 90° (completely vertical). For more on the Slope tool, refer to the following Esri documentation article that describes the different algorithms used to determine slope [6]

High school math refresher:

Slope is calculated as the maximum slope in each direction as calculated by:

slope = arctan(vd/hd)
vd = difference in height (elevation) between the focal pixel and one of its neighbors.
hd = horizontal distance between the focal pixel and one of its neighbors

Slope: Each cell’s value represents elevation

• Open the Slope (Spatial Analysist) tool and set NED2013_mcd_mrp_albers.tif as the input raster
• Save your output as ned13_slope
• Use default settings for all other parameters.
• Run the tool. Remember, this may take a few minutes.
• Take and submit a screenshot of your resulting slope.
• Describe your submission in a couple of sentences.

2.2 Aspect
The Aspect tool computes the direction of the slope. The aspect value is expressed as an azimuth (degrees clockwise from 0° North). For more on the aspect tool, there is an Esri documentation article that describes the different algorithms used to determine aspect [7].

• Use NED2013_mcd_mrp_albers.tif as the input raster and open the Aspect (Spatial Analysist) tool.
• Save your output as ned13_aspect
• There are no other parameters!
When we output the aspect layer, the software automatically assigns classes and colors. Notice the classes are direction-based, e.g. North, South, etc. Do not change the symbology for the aspect - this is industry standard.

• Take and submit a screenshot of your resulting aspect layer.
• Describe your submission in a couple of sentences. Can you think of a use for the aspect tool that’s not covered in the Esri documentation?


2.3 Contours
Contour lines tell us the elevation of a specific horizontal line. From line to line, there is the same amount of elevation change. Lines that are closer together means more elevation change is happening in a shorter horizontal distance ( = STEEP!), and lines that are farther apart means elevation change is happening over a longer horizontal distance ( = flatter)

Contours

Topographic maps usually evoke images of quantitative depictions of relief, using contour lines of equal elevation. We can produce the same using ArcGIS Pro, and we can check our work using the results of the previous step.

• Open the Contour (Spatial Analysist) tool [8].
• Use NED2013_mcd_mrp_albers.tif as the input raster.
    o Name your output feature class ned13_c500m
    o Set the “Contour interval” to 500 (meters).
• For Contour type, select Contour
• Run.
• Add labels to your contours through the Feature Layer ribbon.
    o Customize the text properties and settings for the most readable aesthetic effect.

Hint: Use halos under Symbol Options to create a contrasting white background for your text.

• Take and submit a screenshot of your resulting contours layer.
• Describe your submission in a couple of sentences.

Part 3. The Raster Calculator

Many topographic maps depict relief through shading. The map is shaded according to how the Earth’s surface would be illuminated in natural sunlight (bright, exposed mountains and dark, shaded canyons).
In this section, we are going to demonstrate how the Hillshade [9] tool can be used to produce shaded relief, and how the technique can be achieved (in part) with the Raster Calculator.

3.1 Simple Hillshade using Raster Calculator
The Raster Calculator [10] allows you to calculate an algebraic expression on a cell-wise basis across a raster. You can also use it to perform cell-wise operations on multiple rasters. For example, you can subtract the value of a cell in one raster from the value of the corresponding cell (same x,y coordinates) a different raster. These operations fall under the broad umbrella of Map Algebra operations [11,12]. Let’s implement a simple hillshade using Raster Calculator. The hillshade algorithm is described below.

255.0 * (Cos(Zenith_rad) * Cos(Slope_rad))
    + (Sin(Zenith_rad) * Sin(Slope_rad) * Cos(Azimuth_rad - Aspect_rad))

Where zenith equals the angle of the illumination source (i.e. the sun), above the horizon, and azimuth equals the azimuth of the illumination source.

• Make sure that you have use the original NED2013_mcd_mrp_albers.tif in your workspace.
• Search for and open the Raster Calculator tool
• Translate the above equation into Raster Calculator.
    o Let the illumination zenith = 45° and azimuth = 315°
    o Hint: You can convert from degrees to radians by multiplying by π/180 (approximately 0.01745).
    o For example, you would replace [Slope_rad] with [“ned13_slope” * 0.01745] in Raster Calculator.

This equation works, Maddie promises! If yours isn’t cooperating, check all of your syntax.Do you have the right parentheses? Are you using * not X?

• Save your output as ned_13_hillshade_rc. Take a screenshot for submission.

3.2 Using the Hillshade Tool
ArcGIS Pro features a more sophisticated Hillshade tool [13] that extends our previous example with calculations of local, diffuse illumination and shadow.
• Use NED2013_mcd_mrp_albers.tif as the input raster and open the Hillshade (Spatial Analysist) tool
• Save your output as ned13_hillshade_1
• Check the box for Model Shadows
• Use default settings for all other parameters
• Turn off all other layers except for your original DEM and the Hillshade tool product
    o Turn the hillshade layer transparency to 75% and make it the topmost layer

• Take a screenshot for submission.

Part 5. Ethics in Communicating GIS Information

In emergency response fields, such as firefighting, data are shared quickly. In a dynamic situation like a wildfire, the situation changes quickly as well, meaning the minute a map is finalized, the situation on the ground has already changed. As soon as you save/print/email, the data is already old. Map users must understand that even though the maps are made to inform, there is risk in using them. It is your ethical responsibility as a geographer to be transparent in any shortcomings or constraints.

Write a memo-style short letter (1/2 to 1/3 page, single spaced) to send with the map information your created for the strike team commander. The cover letter should have a clear disclaimer about the intent of the maps (to provide background/terrain information to support their strategic planning), information about when they were finalized, and how to get in touch with you (i.e. contact info). Include a formal statement modeled off these links, but adapted and streamlined to fit our specific scenario.

https://gis.stackexchange.com/questions/13514/providing-warnings-and-accuracy-features-on-map-for-legal-reasons

https://www.aacounty.org/county-maps/data-download/GIS_Disclaimer.pdf

http://gis.clark.wa.gov/custom52/mapsonline/includes/legal.html

You’re welcome to search for additional sources for information/inspiration.
